    "recap_headline": "Seton Hall University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "South Orange, N.J. \u2013\nMason Christopher\ndazzled once again, allowing just three hits and two runs over six innings of work as the Pirates took the rubber match of their weekend series with Hofstra on Sunday, 6-2.\nHow it Happened\nThe Hall's bats made noise early, scoring four times in the second to grab an early lead. After three straight singles to open the frame,\nMagnus Krieger\nlaced a double over the head of the center fielder to plate the first two runs of the day. Two productive outs followed, as\nFrankie Scrivanic\nhad an RBI groundout and\nTommy Manzo\nhit a sacrifice fly to give the hosts a 4-0 lead.\nB2 | Magnus gets us on the board \ud83d\udcaa\npic.twitter.com/5BCG75jsea\n\u2014 Seton Hall University Baseball (@SHUBaseball)\nMarch 22, 2026\nOn the mound, Christopher was cruising. The lefty set down the first 13 batters he faced, allowing his first hit of the day with one out in the top of the fifth. Hofstra was able to tack on two runs against Christopher in the fifth, but the sophomore was able to work a clean sixth to end his outing on a high note.\nThe Pirates were able to get those two runs back in the sixth. Acker and Krieger led off the inning with singles, and a fly ball from Scrivanic moved Acker down to third with one out.\nTommy Manzo\nexecuted a perfect safety squeeze bunt up the first base line, scoring Acker with the fifth Seton Hall run.\nGabe Cavazzoni\nstepped in as the lineup flipped back over and rocketed an RBI triple to the gap in right center, scoring Krieger to give Seton Hall a 6-2 edge.\nThe Pirate bullpen closed the door from there.\nStephen Curry\nworked two scoreless innings, but surrendered a double to lead off the top of the ninth.\nJohn Higgins\ncame on to finish the job, working himself into and out of a bases loaded jam to preserve the victory.\nUp Next\nSeton Hall finishes its eight-game homestand on Wednesday afternoon at 4 p.m. when it hosts Princeton.",
